<+>---\nlayout: archive\ntitle: \"Welcome to osLyricHouse\"\npermalink: /oslyrichouse/\nauthor_profile: true\n---\nosLyricHouse is a lyric sharing platform, and one of the first of its kind.<br> \nThe best way to explain this is to take you through the basic navigation of a new user.<br>\n***\n\" I been listening to ******** on repeat and can't get it out of my head!\"br>\nWe've all been there. We find that song and we just can't stop listening to it. Sometimes literally don't let the song end! And as if waiting for the perfect moment or vibe to hit, we hit restart hoping to pick up more.\nTypically we like the music we relate to right? We hear that song and immediately can relate to every word. It hits you differently.\nosLyricHouse not only encourages you to personalize but collaborate with the world in a way that easy for anyone to pick up the application and start contributing.\nA big part of osLyricHouse that I want to make clear is that it is not trying to plagiarize, or market content that is and should be paid content. In that context, all submissions and content on osLyricHouse are heavily filtered to make sure proper credit is given to the mainstream producers and artists.\n 99% of the content you find on osLyricHouse is user-submitted lyrics that are written to music that is already produced. \nnow, let me see your remix of your favorite Imagine Dragons song.\nThere are many features that I want to implement into osLyricHouse, but there is one current feature that I want to preserve from the development phase through production. The 'os' in osLyricHouse stands for Open Source. If in the future there is some kind of subscription service of some kind all profits would go to my education and obviously anyone employed to build and/or maintain the application.\nThere are so many talented individuals in our world that need another vector of expression. I don't know how mainstream artists will feel about it. Hopefully, they encourage it. although promoting is not what osLyricHouse is about, we do out of our way to make sure any outward-directed links to music is pointed to more direct sources than say YouTube\n
